# arc-runner.user-md -- project rules for multi-step workers (Berreman)

This is the Berreman project prompt piece that pairs with the
cross-repo `arc-runner.system-md`. The arc-runner passes both
paths to each worker session; the worker reads this file *second*
(after the system prompt) for project-specific rules.

This file lives at `./.user-md/Berreman/arc-runner.user-md`
(repo-root relative).

**Usage (arc-runner-driven, never user-typed):**

```
Do the task <slice-spec-path> using
<this-tool-repo>/src/ai_strategy_generator/multistep/arc-runner.system-md
and ./.user-md/Berreman/arc-runner.user-md.
```

**Example:**

```
Do the task ./specs/001-01-scratch-one.md using
<this-tool-repo>/src/ai_strategy_generator/multistep/arc-runner.system-md
and ./.user-md/Berreman/arc-runner.user-md.
```

`<this-tool-repo>` resolves to the AI-Strategy-Generator clone
location on the host machine.

---

## Project shape

Berreman is a pure F# numerical optics solver. The solution
file is `Berreman/Berreman.slnx`; the test project is
`Berreman/BerremanTests/BerremanTests.fsproj`. Related projects
under `Berreman/`:

- `Berreman/Berreman/` -- the core solver (matrix math, eigen
  decomposition, Fourier transforms, field functions).
- `Berreman/OpticalModel/`, `Berreman/OpticalProperties/` --
  data types for optical stacks and materials.
- `Berreman/BerremanRunner/` -- the CLI / batch runner.
- `Berreman/BerremanModelGenerator/` -- generates model
  parameter sets.
- `Berreman/Analytics/` -- analytics helpers.
- `Berreman/BerremanTests/` -- F# unit tests covering the core
  solver and adjacent modules.

There is no UI, no Android, no A/V harness, no emulator. Worker
sessions only need `dotnet` on PATH (which is the case on this
machine).

---

## Build tool

```
dotnet build Berreman.slnx -c Release
```

Run from the `Berreman/` subdirectory (the `build` gate's `cwd`
is set there). The same `dotnet build` invocation is what the
`build` gate runs -- if your local build is green, that gate
will be green too (modulo environment drift).

There is no MSBuild requirement for this project -- `dotnet
build` resolves and builds the `.slnx` directly.

---

## Testing procedure

```
dotnet test --no-build -c Release
```

Run from the `Berreman/BerremanTests/` subdirectory (the
`unit-tests` gate's `cwd` is set there). The tests are pure F#
unit tests across numerical kernels (matrix ops, eigenvectors,
Fourier transforms, rotation matrices, advanced solver, etc.).
Run them after every code change to the core solver or its
adjacent projects.

There is no separate integration-test or smoke-test suite for
this project yet. If a slice introduces one, propose a new
`.gates/Berreman/<name>.gates` descriptor first.

---

## Gates

The arc-runner reads each slice's gate set from the manifest's
`slice_gates:` block. For Berreman, the default set is:

- `impl-log-structure` (root) -- structural check on the impl-log MD.
- `state-of-world-structure` (root) -- structural check on the SoW MD.
- `build` (`Berreman/`) -- `dotnet build` of the solution.
- `unit-tests` (`Berreman/`) -- `dotnet test` against `BerremanTests`.

What you need to know while implementing:

- **Every slice runs every gate in its set**, in the order
  declared. First failure short-circuits.
- **`count_at_least` gates** (unit tests) pass when the captured
  count is at least the baseline from the prior slice's
  state-of-the-world YAML block. For the first slice of an arc,
  the baseline is 0, so any passing count works.
- **The `state-of-world-structure` gate** is an arc-runner-side
  check that your state-of-the-world file exists and contains
  the required ATX section headings: `Where we are`,
  `What's working`, `Tests`, `Architecture`, `Deferred`,
  `Gotchas`, `Changelog`. Omitting this file or any required
  heading fails the gate.

---

## Code style

This project does not yet carry a top-level `CLAUDE.MD` /
`AGENTS.md` style guide. Default to standard F# conventions:
PascalCase for module / function / type names, camelCase for
locals, four-space indent, no `open` of project-internal
namespaces unless the file uses 3+ symbols from them. Numerical
code should preserve the existing precedent for floating-point
tolerance (look at `MatrixComparison.fs` for the project's
chosen comparison helpers).

If the user adds a top-level style guide later, this section
should defer to it.

---

Per the layout in `arc-runner.system-md`, the per-arc artifacts
folder is `<specs_root>/<spec_id>/.artifacts/` (the supervisor
resolves the concrete absolute path and passes it to the worker
via the task file). Worker code MUST route persistent output to
sub-paths of that folder; never to `%TEMP%/...` or
`%LOCALAPPDATA%/...`.

---

## Commit attribution

**Drop the hard-coded
`Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>`
line**. Replace with `Co-Authored-By: <model> <noreply@<provider>>`
derived from the resolved backend.

---

## Critics

Per-project critic hook. The arc-runner reads the fenced YAML
below at boot, validates each `id` against
`src/schemas/multistep/`, and slots each project critic into the
critic + judge sub-loop after its `run_after` dependencies.
Berreman declares no project critics yet -- the built-in
`architecture_critic` and `reuse_critic` cover the common cases
for this project's numerical / analytics shape.

```yaml
critics: []
```

No project may add a second judge (the `code_judge` is the single
decision point per cycle); the supervisor refuses to start when an
entry's `id` is reserved.

---

## Don't ask the user

The arc-runner is the reviewer. The user is NOT watching the
worker session. If the slice spec is ambiguous, pick the
interpretation most consistent with `arc-runner.system-md`, with
this file, and with the surrounding code -- and record the
choice you made in the impl-log's `Gotchas` section.

Prompts that wait for user input will stall the whole round and
escalate after the retry is also stalled. The arc-runner's
workaround is "kill the stalled console and try again once" --
not a replacement for picking a sensible default and noting it.

---

## Operator note

This section is reserved as a stable insertion point for the
arc-runner supervisor. The supervisor injects the operator's
reply text from the previous escalation here on the first
attempt of a resumed slice. When no operator reply is in flight
this heading remains present but empty. Workers MUST read
whatever lands under this heading before acting on the slice
spec; an operator note may add scope constraints or override the
spec for that attempt.
